:: At the Corner of Dean Street and Greek Street {"position":"1200,400","size":"100,100"}
A man, not much past twenty, stands under a ginger light. At first you think he must be a dilly boy. He wears a beret and paints his nails; he is epicene and crinoline, as if he might snap at any moment.

Then you clock him for a poet that you know. A poet called Red.

<span class="guided-link">[[Wait for him to speak|You wait for him to speak]]</span>
[[Speak to him|You speak to the poet]]


